## Level 28 → Level 29
**Objective:** Clone a git repository where the password has been
redacted in the latest commit — recover it from git history.

**Commands Used:**
```bash
git clone ssh://bandit28-git@bandit.labs.overthewire.org:2220/home/bandit28-git/repo bandit28repo
                                        # cloned into custom local folder name
                                        # 'repo' already existed from last level
cd bandit28repo                         # moved into cloned repository
ls                                      # found README.md
cat README.md                           # password showed as xxxxxxxxxx — redacted
git log                                 # checked commit history — found 3 commits
git show 8b7c651b37ce7a94633b7b7b7c980ded19a16e4f
                                        # viewed second commit contents
                                        # found the real password
```

**Why `repo` Folder Already Existed:**
- Last level cloned a repo into a folder called `repo`
- Git refuses to clone into an existing non-empty folder
- Solution: specify a custom local folder name at the end of
  the clone command as a separate argument
```bash
git clone <url> foldername    # clones into custom named folder
git clone <url> bandit28repo  # example used here
```

**URL Path vs Local Folder Name:**
```
git clone ssh://user@host:port/home/bandit28-git/repo    bandit28repo
                               │                          │
                               └── Server repo path       └── Local folder name
                               (never change this)         (you choose this)
```

**What the Git Log Showed:**
```
commit 1 — "fix info leak"     ← newest, current, password redacted
commit 2 — "add missing data"  ← password was added here (target)
commit 3 — initial commit      ← basic setup
```

**Why the Password Was Still Recoverable:**
- Git tracks every change ever made to a repository
- Deleting or changing data in a new commit does NOT erase history
- Every previous commit is permanently stored and retrievable
- `git show commitID` displays exactly what changed in that commit
- This is a real world vulnerability — developers often accidentally
  commit passwords and then try to "fix" it by overwriting in a
  new commit, not realizing the history is permanent

**How to Read `git show` Output:**
```
- password: xxxxxxxxxx    ← line removed in this commit (shown in red)
+ password: xxxxxxxxxx    ← line added in this commit (shown in green)
```
- Lines starting with `-` = what was removed
- Lines starting with `+` = what was added
- The removed line (`-`) shows the original password

**What I Learned:**
- Git history is permanent — overwriting sensitive data in a new
  commit does not erase it from history
- `git log` shows all commits with their IDs, authors and messages
- `git show commitID` reveals exactly what changed in that commit
- Commit messages are clues — "fix info leak" immediately signals
  something sensitive was removed
- Always check git history when current files look sanitized

**Real Pentesting Relevance:**
Exposed credentials in git history is one of the most common
real world vulnerabilities found in bug bounty and pentesting:
- API keys accidentally committed then "deleted"
- Database passwords in config files
- Private keys pushed to public repositories
- Internal URLs and infrastructure details
Tools like **truffleHog** and **git-secrets** automatically
scan git history for sensitive data patterns.

**Key Takeaway:**
Never trust that sensitive data is gone just because it was
removed in a later commit. Git history tells the whole story.
In real pentesting always run `git log` and check suspicious
commit messages like "remove password", "fix leak", "delete key"
— these are red flags that something sensitive was there before.
